Here are the local ‘vin du pays’ wines of France that bring so much joy to tourists who explore the French countryside. Each has its own personality, its own message, its own touch of charm. They were not easy to come by since many of the growers are not export-minded. Undoubtedly, you have heard about some of them, have read of their virtues in literature—and we happily bring them to you.

RED COUNTRY WINES

Bottle Case VIN DE CORSE 1970 1.49 16.50

Nicolas found this big, fat country red wine for us on the island of Corsica. Similar to a Cote-du-Rhone Rouge.

CORBIERES CHAINTRUEL 1.49 16.50 Nicolas sends us this excellent red wine grown on the rolling hills of Carcassonne.

LANGUEDOC ROUGE 1970... 1.59 17.15 Here is what all Paris is drinking and this one from Nicolas is the best of the lot. Lusty, flavorsome, and an outstanding example of what the French call ‘vin rouge.’

PROVENCE ROUGE 1970.............. 1.69 18.25 Nicolas. the famed Parisian wine merchants, buy this wine in vast quantities and get the best. Their purchasing savings are passed on to you.

FITOU (Pyrences) 6s 1.79 19.35 No vintage appears on the label, but it is actually a 1969— the best red wine of the French Midi. Full-bodied, vigorous.

LES BAUX ROUGE 1968................ 2.20 24.75 Estate-bottled at Mas de la Dame vineyard, residence of Mr. Faye, President of the company that produces Cinzano, Dubonnet, Cusenier and Pernod. His personal pride is re- flected in the wine.

GAMAY DE SAVOIE 1969.............. 2.49 26.90 Gamay, the grape of Beaujolais, takes on an interesting new character when grown on the slopes of the Alps.

IRANCY 1969 (Burgundy).............. 2.69 29.05 Irancy is a village 10 miles southwest of Chablis in northern Burgundy. It is fresh, delightful, and should be served slightly cool as a red wine to accompany the steaks and the hamburgers as they come off the grill.

CAHORS 1967 22) ee: 2.79 30.15 Interesting legendary red wine grown north of Toulouse, and not far from the famed medieval Chateau de Mercués. Dark crimson in color, long-lived, similar to a full-bodied red wine in Graves. Estate-bottled, Parnac.

BANDOL ROUGE 1964................-. 2.99 32.30 Estate-bottled, Chateau Pradeaux. Considered the best red wine of all Provence. Grown on terraces overlooking the Bandol fishing village.

BOUZY ROUGE 1966

PINK COUNTRY WINES (French Vin Rose)

Bottle Case VIN DE CORSE ROSE 1969 1.49 16.50 Lusty and dry. From Corsica. Nicolas. PROVENCE ROSE 1969 1.69 18.25 A spritely pink grown near Mediterranean. Nicolas. CABERNET ROSE 1969 1.79 19.35

Produced in the Anjou area of the Loire Valley, made from the superior Cabernet grape, providing more depth and flavor than the average Anjou Rose. Nicolas.

LIRAC ROSE 1969 1.99 21.50 This estate-bottling by Domaine Closel recently won the First Gold Award at the Paris fair as the best within its class. The vineyard is adjacent to Tavel, made of the same Gre- nache grape, and is quite undistinguishable from Tavel itself. This one is an absolute beauty.

TAVEL ROSE 1970.......... 2.49 26.90 No ordinary Tavel this one, it is estate-bottled by M. Bernard. It is of the current 1970 vintage, its youth retaining its color, fruit and freshness. Because the soil is arid and rocky, the yield per acre is small, resulting in more flavor and bouquet than is usually associated with a rosé.

CASTEL ROUBINE ........ 2.49 26.90 Fstate-bottled at outstanding vineyard in Provence. Con- sidered the best rosé of area.

CASSIS ROSE 1969 3 ee 2.49 26.90 Made from Grenache grape in delightful town of Cassis on the Mediterranean. Estate-bottled, Domaine du Paternel. ROSE DE SANCERRE 1969............ 2.59 27.95 Amazing rosé from town of Sancerre in Loire. Estate-bottled, V. Delaporte.

BOURGOGNE ROSE 1969........... 2.69 29.05 Made from Pinot Noir grape on Marsannay soil. Perhaps the best rosé of all France. Estate-bottled, André Bart.
